  "prompt": "How much money in charitable donations can a person deduct from his/her taxes before being taxed on his/her donations in the US?",
  "response": "In the United States, the IRS allows individuals to deduct charitable donations from their taxable income if they itemize their deductions. As of the current tax laws, individuals can generally deduct up to 60% of their adjusted gross income (AGI) for donations to qualifying charities. However, this limit can vary based on the type of donation and the organization receiving the donation.\n\nFor example:\n1. Donations of cash to public charities and certain private foundations: Up to 60% of AGI.\n2. Donations of appreciated assets (such as stocks or real estate) to public charities: Usually up to 30% of AGI.\n3. Donations to certain private foundations, veterans organizations, fraternal societies, and cemetery organizations: Up to 30% of AGI (for cash) and 20% of AGI (for appreciated assets).\n\nIt\u2019s important to note that if your total charitable contributions exceed these limits, the excess can often be carried forward and deducted in future years, usually for up to five years.\n\nBecause tax laws are complex and can frequently change, it\u2019s advisable to consult with a tax professional or refer to the latest IRS guidelines for accurate and personalized advice.",
